body:
> a perfect solution would be an extendable files_external plugin, where the different backends are hosted as "standalone" apps, which simply integrate into the core plugin. this would allow easier integration of new backends (which is your concern no. 3) and it would also take the burden of supporting and maintaining them away from the core developers.

@crazyphil if you modify the files_external app to allow storage backends to 'register' with it for the purpose of configuration then i would gladly accept that code into core. so, just moving the getbackends() part out of the configuration class and into the storages. 

you can then ship your rapidshare storage as an app without the additional files_external app code for configuring it.

@mtgap: i've modified the files_external app to have backends register themselves before being able to use them. the amount of changes is (in my opinion) in an acceptable range and the default backends work as before, so that there should no problems arise.

the only downside with a push (backend registers itself) instead of a pull (app searches for backends in all app directories) approach is that the backend has to make sure the files_external app is already loaded before trying to register ("if files_external is enabled then load it and register backend, else do nothing"). this case happens if users first enable the backend app and then the files_external app. the upside is that there is no "magic" involved with finding and registering backends and all potential backend developers are aware of what to do to get them into the list. do you think this approach is acceptable? do you want to see the code before i open yet another pull request?

@raydiation: the amount of shared code is huge. when creating an app that just consists of a storage backend, you only need the classes for this specific backend and the app "metadata" files. the management functionality can fully be done by the files_external app.
